ascents.comment: One of my favorites I've done in my short year climbing in the front range... if this is still considered front range.
Fun! Went quite a bit quicker than dark waters stand.
Awesome. Feels like a 6.
Worth the hike/scramble over the boulders
Fun considering it's size. Not sure on the grade, but went significantly quicker than a 10 normally goes for me.
I like the jump move.
Worked/sent solo, couple areas to be careful not to swing off that nice landing.
Campused the crimps, grabbed one sloper then jumped for the jug. Mega fun but the jump to the jug would make for a nasty fall if you lost it mid swing.
Stumbled upon it on accident but was well worth the stop.
Guidebook seems to indicate small or no feet... W/ a toehook feels more v4/5 range, especially compared to the unnamed V7 down the hill.
Couldn't pull off the shorty beta, ended up tossing a toe hook around right and it made for some really fun but stretched out movement. Took more tries than other V7s of the trip.
Humid after work sesh turn into crisp evening temps for a relatively quick send after sorting out beta. From left hand low start.
Roasted in the heat figuring out the beta, a cloud and a cool breeze made everything come together. Tried crimp beta for fun and it felt a good bit harder than the compression.
Psyched for a pre work send. Felt hard and took a while to come together.

Glad to see this getting traffic and settling into the grade. Worked on the FA for a full session in 2019. Was surprised to find forcing movement and it looks like others have taken the same path. Would be a classic if not for the dab potential and funky top. Check out some beta here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cCnjlfiTGS0
Worked solo, never felt like I quite had the right beta. That start reach. yikes.
Gotta love some squeezing on a sharp rock. Glad I didn't have to work this one much. Second or third try.

Sent right before the shutdown. Things were already getting weird as this boulders popularity seemed to be peaking. Needed cool temps to stick to that crimp. Really came down to holding the swing. Need to work on hip flexibility.
Worked in the sun, send in the sun. Would feel great on a cold day.
Hard in 100% humidity but still a fun worthwhile climb. Easy to access and safe landing for a short solo mission.
HMM... Hmm... hmm ... hm . m
Hmmm hmmm hmm hm m
First go second session. Felt very easy with beta sorted and good conditions
Nice pad party with a seasonal bro squad.
Lovely warm day in Jan. Dabby but fun movement. Would be five stars without the boulder behind the finishing moves
Lovely warm day in Jan. Dabby but fun movement. Would be five stars without the boulder behind the finishing moves
Agreed one of the best anywhere!
One day working it, first go next day after warming up on a few of the finish moves.
Gimme after Flower Power.
Gotta love the classics. Felt light on this. Promptly tried the sit, foot slipped and bonked my head into the wall. That'll teach me to feel light.
Veggies for a few days in my blender making this blender feel not so bad.

Left variation into The Rhino V11. Started on left-hand pinch and undercling crimp as low as possible. Long right hand reach to another sharp undercling. Cross to crimp or jug and make a few moderate moves to get into the rhino. This seems to be lower than what's in the guide book but seems fair to soft for the grade.

Took an hour to not do any of the moves. Then did each move individually and sent first try from the start. Weird. Felt impossible then easy. First time I've done a barefoot ascent. Recommending just for novelty.

Started low matched on huecos in the cave. Left-hand slap to the lip. R to meat hook left to a sloping hold on the lip. Some foot trickery to cross up to the jugs. Harder than other V5's I've been on around Hueco, will go ahead and be the first to upgrade.
Ass drag to ass pucker. Kinda liked it more than I want to admit.

First go ~4th session after 4 rest days. Maybe I should rest more. Felt great executing my beta on a cool after-work session. Fun working it for a few days while Bruce, Wes, and Austin worked variations. Will probably be back for Wheel next winter or tomorrow who knows.
Super soft although the sit feels about right somehow.

Got suckered into toe hook beta before switching back to pogo jump/shoulder move. Went quick after switching back... I wish the toe hook sequence was forced because it's more moves and cool... It's short-lived with the jump beta.

Third go, close on the flash but didn't pay enough attention. Oh well, psyched to be out climbing for my bday weekend somewhere new and gotta love the sandbagged local test pieces. A little sharp on the fingies.
Third go probably harder than anorexic if you don't campus.
Nice to have beta. Felt good after working in moon roof all morning.
Classic V3 that's probably not v3 even with beta but a fun problem never the less. A little contrived with the wall off and it's traversing nature.

Fastest 10 to date. Second go second session. Felt lucky to do it early in the session. Power endurance to a fun couple of power jumpy moves. Time to try some of the variations if I can find time this trip!
Guide said V7 probably about right going start to pocket right hand, a tough lever, then some campusy feet first action to get around the lip.
Second go with good beta and fresh body. One of the best in Flagstaff I've done during this 1.5 week trip.
Not my favorite. Didn't think the shoulder move was bad. The sharp ass pockets are painful. The finish was awkward. The 360 was cool.
Didn't really fit the knees. Feeling good on underlings but tough send on an 80-degree day. Third go third day. Wish the lines were a little more independent but the movement is great.
Went quick once I figured my feet out for the start. 1 sesh after lots of other try hard on a hot day. Just jumped between jugs.
Warmed up on the moves then did fairly quick with some wack beta after watching vids. Never the less really enjoyed it! Felt like a moonboard problem tucked in the backwoods of Montana.

I didn't think I'd like rocking over the left and would want to stay on the arete. Turns out it's forcing and pretty cool rolling over left. Excited to try variations. V7 sounds fair but a bit easier than Carpenter crack.
Hmm, apparently I missed a drop knee. Did it with a smeary left foot and a powerful thrutch. Felt hard but as far as contrived lines go it wasn't the worst.
Why?
Afterwork special. Classic squeezy endurance boulder.

That top out though... 
Fun squeeze rig. Seemingly nonstandard beta bumping left hand up to arete then a right-hand heel match to bring right hand up to the sharp but good part of the arete. Enjoyed it more on a cold windy day.
Enjoyed it. Coming back for the sit.
meh, felt sharp. Silly start.
Did it four or five years ago but logging this day flash cause it'd be nice to remember it this time. A little sharp but cool temps help.

Stand - Agree with Brett... Tried intermittently over the years with the heinous mantle beta. As soon as I started reaching for the right hold it went pretty quick. Still hard with my lack of hip mobility but it's improving!

HAMM poon poon. First 10 in a sesh first day in Bishop. Seemed unlikely at first but it came together towards the end of hour 3... Probably on the softer side but I have been climbing pretty well this week so maybe 10 is fair... Comfier holds or a better top and it'd be five star in my book but still really enjoyed it. Now I need a rest day.
3rd go. Sharpy mcsharpness. Still, it was pretty fun.

Took longer than I care to admit but once the stand went the sit went nextt sesh. Watched the first left hand turn into a jug over the years... Maybe it was a v12 prior to that chockstone getting pulled out. Feels good to have it under the belt and not ever do that mantle again.
A hot meatball full of glass.
Nice way to end the year. Got on this years ago was nice to do it quick this go-round. Figuring out the right feet took the first move from feeling impossible to going next try.
Not as scary as you might think once you're moving. Super fun and aesthetic.
BWT - Buck Wild Times

About as fun as they come. The stand went quick and almost did this the next sesh... Alas, 4 sessions later it came together but still took some try hard to keep those top two moves together. This one really seems to favor the tall.
Need more hips... hipshipships Nice couple punch moves but a little sharp. I forget what these numbers mean.
Wasn't warm and grew a steel rod in my trap that is making me think I need more... Therapy.

First "warm-up" go of the day. Love when that happens. Getting around the corner clean took a small miracle! Would be four or five stars if not for the dabalicious ending and people deciding to poop in the cave.
Choo choo.. I guess I'll hop on the points train! Took many less tries than beefcake ¯\_(ツ)_/¯

Stars for movement and relative comfort. Managed to turn the last two sessions into an epic by punting off the last shouldery jug move a dozen times before pulling my life together and doing the damn move late in the day. Despite its frustratingly finicky nature I'm actually really psyched to do this... feeling leveled up in my power endurance after a 2min 38 sec send go.
A few different options for the finishes. I've done 2/3 at the time of writing. Feels hard for a fiver.
Squoze despite the hot hot heat. Harder than beefcake but then again maybe it's the hottness. Hot caves hot cakes.

Hiked to emerald to find whispers wet... Came here to find this block soaked. Made it harder than necessary eliminating the wet holds along the crack and using a crimp on the face. Fun. Did some moves on SAP I think. A little sharp but a nice line.
Did the moves to warm up, second go. Working into the 9... want more pads. Nice movement and holds.

First go, third day. Punted the top on day two a few times... Then had a ridiculous send go missing the final jug and about peeling off. Made for a good dramatic moment. Enjoyed this one. Not sure if the heat made it hard or if it's just hard. Either way took me longer than most 9s but really enjoyed the process
Start of second session. Not that bad. No toehook but did use knee scums. Left exit. Really digging way lake so far.
Just needed to sacrifice my lunch to the crash pad and some crispy crispy tempuras.

It lived up to the hype. Harder than I wanted. Almost flashed but swung off that finish jug... quite a few times... then it took me three sessions soooo here we are. All that aside one of the best around and worth waiting for an evening session to not get nuked in the alpine sun.

Shoulda put some proper thought/prep for the flash. Thinking toehook start takes this down a notch. You can also knee bar the arete to pull around the lip. Don't think it's V9 with my beta. Start crimp *****

After three days of skin sacrifices to the crystal demons of front-range granite gods a brisk 90 mph wind and 40-degree temps was enough to harden my one last thread of ramen fingers for a first go, last go, best go, let's go... Actually really enjoyed this thing despite the few frustrating punts it took to get it done. Probably one of the few to use a knee pad to turn the lip... give it a try!
My shin abs are poppin!!
Shin abs ftw again. Thanks for warming the toe grabbers up Captain Hook. Can't take 10 since I don't second-go 10s. Climbs nicely but has no aesthetics.
Felt great through and through. Really nice waiting for some crispy temps. One of the best I've been on.
First go second day after three punts in the sun the prior session. Actually liked it more than I thought I would once it's done.

Considering how twin cracks felt...
Took 5-6 tries and used some feet out right to just pull up to the sloper. /hard/
Used the lower hold, bumped and did a wild move to the last good side pull. Very nice climb, needed pads to reach the start.
Cool little climb on the east rim. Felt good after a long warm-up. Didn't flash the five next door.
Took a couple tries.
ascents.zlaggableName: Jug Start to Acid Wash Right

ascents.comment: Nice climb, like water over water.
That little crimp made the start feel chill. Not my favorite but glad it's done and feels easy now.

Compared to the right version, slow dance or standing kill order this was quite a bit harder for me. Those all went in a session really just a couple rp goes. This one took three sessions. Did it with shorter beta bumping into that right-hand crimp under cling.   Grades are funny but I feel given the effort required this lines up more with 10s than 9's in my book. ¯\_(ツ)_/¯
Cool first move. In a sesh... after a long day. Pulling on the fish trombones probably had my pocket fingers ready to go.
ascents.zlaggableName: Hit the High Hard One, Sit

ascents.comment: Dancing up the right side while squirreling a NEE bar in that hueco. Enjoyed the compression and the tall top.

Thanks Chat GPT

Oh boy, let me tell you about this "amazing" rock climb that I just did. It was good, I suppose, but definitely not perfect. The climb had its moments, but it was nothing to write home about. The rock face was challenging enough to make me work for it, but not so much that I was in danger of falling to my death. I mean, come on, where's the fun in that? 

I must admit, I had my doubts about this climb from the start. It just didn't seem like it was going to be anything special. And yet, here I am, having completed it and feeling... well, not exactly thrilled, but not entirely disappointed either. It was kind of like eating a sandwich that's just okay. You're not exactly excited about it, but it's still better than going hungry.

All in all, I guess I'm glad I did this climb. It was a decent way to spend a few hours, and it did provide me with a sense of accomplishment, however minor. But let's not kid ourselves, it was far from perfect. If you're looking for a truly epic climb, this is not it. But if you're just looking to kill some time and get a bit of exercise, then go for it.
I'll hop on the loco for now but might change my mind later and take v8 for this. Contrived, added extra moves like the lefthand bump to make a little harder and at the end.
Took a couple of tries. Liked it more than I expected to. One of my few moments in the sun/year. Chat GPT make this description more interesting please.

In the depths of the earth it sleeps,
For seven long years, it barely peeps.
Unseen, unheard, it bides its time,
Till the moment comes to climb and climb V9.

Emerging from its earthen tomb,
The cicada spreads its wings to bloom.
Its life is but a fleeting thing,
A song to sing, a dance to fling.

With eyes that shine like beads of black,
It searches for a mate to track.
And in a moment, in a trice,
The cicada mates, then pays the price.

For soon its song will fade away,
Its dance will end, its life will stray.
Back to the earth, it falls to sleep,
For seven long years, it barely peeps.

And so the cycle will repeat,
The cicada's life, a bittersweet.
A fleeting moment in the sun,
A lifetime spent, but just begun.

So let us pause, and take a breath,
And ponder on this life and death.
For like the cicada, we too will pass,
A fleeting moment, in the grass.

Landing makes ya think... A sport climber's V9... Used some jump beta on the bottom crux
Third go... then did the start about 10 more times trying to get Paths. Next time hopefully.

really lived up to its name... This thing was pretty wild. Barely there on the go. So elated and out of breath. I really enjoyed this one and really had to work for it. Put together a little beta video. https://youtu.be/VaDS6IULpLA
Went from impossible to not so bad after a couple of core and shoulder exercises.

Wow, it's been a minute since this one has been logged. Felt on par for the grade once conditions rolled in after sunset but could see why the first move or the jump move would be tough for some. Enjoyed it way more than I expected mostly for the fantastic movement. Wild shoulder move, dropping in to match a sick toe hook to a cut loose compy style dyno into a sucker punch.
